def make_subset(subset_name, start_index, end_index):
    for category in ("cat", "dog"):
        target_dir = new_base_dir / subset_name / category
        os.makedirs(target_dir, exist_ok=True)  # Safer: won't error if folder exists
        fnames = [f"{category}.{i}.jpg" for i in range(start_index, end_index)]
        for fname in fnames:
            shutil.copyfile(original_dir / fname, target_dir / fname)

make_subset("train", 0, 1000)
make_subset("validation", 1000, 1500)
make_subset("test", 1500, 2500)

Train Custom CNN Model¶

In [7]:
def build_custom_model():
    model = models.Sequential([
        layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(img_height, img_width, 3)),
        layers.MaxPooling2D(2, 2),
        layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
        layers.MaxPooling2D(2, 2),
        layers.Flatten(),
        layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'),
        layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
    ])
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

custom_model = build_custom_model()
custom_cb = callbacks.ModelCheckpoint('best_custom_model.h5', save_best_only=True, monitor='val_loss')
custom_model.fit(train_gen, validation_data=val_gen, epochs=10, callbacks=[custom_cb])

Train Fine-Tuned VGG16 Model¶

In [8]:
vgg_base = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(img_height, img_width, 3))
vgg_base.trainable = False

vgg_model = models.Sequential([
    vgg_base,
    layers.Flatten(),
    layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'),
    layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])

vgg_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
vgg_cb = callbacks.ModelCheckpoint('best_vgg_model.h5', save_best_only=True, monitor='val_loss')
vgg_model.fit(train_gen, validation_data=val_gen, epochs=10, callbacks=[vgg_cb])

Evaluate Model Performance¶

In [9]:
def evaluate_model(model, generator, name="Model"):
    generator.reset()
    pred_probs = model.predict(generator)
    preds = (pred_probs > 0.5).astype(int)
    y_true = generator.classes

    acc = np.mean(preds.flatten() == y_true)
    print(f"{name} Accuracy: {acc:.4f}")

    print(confusion_matrix(y_true, preds))
    print(classification_report(y_true, preds))

    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_true, pred_probs)
    f1 = f1_score(y_true, preds)
    print(f"{name} F1-Score: {f1:.4f}")

    plt.plot(recall, precision)
    plt.xlabel('Recall')
    plt.ylabel('Precision')
    plt.title(f'{name} Precision-Recall Curve')
    plt.show()

    return preds

print("\nEvaluating Custom CNN:")
custom_model.load_weights('best_custom_model.h5')
preds_custom = evaluate_model(custom_model, test_gen, name="Custom CNN")

print("\nEvaluating VGG16 Model:")
vgg_model.load_weights('best_vgg_model.h5')
preds_vgg = evaluate_model(vgg_model, test_gen, name="VGG16")

Show Failure Cases¶

In [10]:
def show_failure_cases(generator, predictions):
    generator.reset()
    x, y = next(generator)
    for i in range(10):
        if predictions[i] != y[i]:
            plt.imshow(x[i])
            plt.title(f'True: {int(y[i])}, Pred: {int(predictions[i])}')
            plt.axis('off')
            plt.show()
            break

print("\nFailure cases (Custom CNN):")
show_failure_cases(test_gen, preds_custom)

print("\nFailure cases (VGG16):")
show_failure_cases(test_gen, preds_vgg)

Conclusions¶

This practical study used a balanced Dogs vs. Cats dataset to evaluate a customized CNN with a refined VGG16 model. The VGG16 fared noticeably better with 88.25% accuracy and an F1-score of 0.882 than the custom CNN, which had 67.7% accuracy and an F1-score of 0.653. The usefulness of transfer learning, particularly with limited data, is demonstrated by the VGG16 model's improved performance.

Failure instances showed that both models had trouble with stylized or confusing images, indicating that more sophisticated architectures or data augmentation could help. All things considered, VGG16 was a more dependable option for this binary classification challenge.
